<TEXT>
paraguays authoritarian government 
has withdrawn its ban on a meeting between pope john paul ii and a 
civic group that includes opposition politicians the vatican said 
friday 
a statement read to reporters traveling with the pope in 
neighboring bolivia said the meeting tuesday in asuncion capital 
of paraguay will be held just as planned 
the announcement came as the pontiff urged bolivians at this 
cocaine crossroads to make war on the drug trade that sows your 
soil with corruption and death 
in lima peru where the pope was due to arrive saturday 
afternoon about 60 leftist guerrillas marching past a hotel 
housing the papal press center stoned and firebombed the building 
friday night police and witnesses said 
windows were broken and a small fire caused by a firebomb was 
quickly extinguished police said no injuries were reported 
earlier this week midway through a 12day papal tour of four 
south american countries gen alfredo stroessners paraguayan 
government canceled john pauls scheduled meeting with the builders 
of society 
about 350 intellectuals businessmen and politicians belong to 
the group which is sponsored by the church and includes 
representatives of unauthorized opposition parties 
paraguay said the ban was for security reasons the vatican 
said it was astonished at the unprecedented step 
according to the statement the reversal was arranged at a 
meeting between paraguayan government representatives and the 
vatican ambassador and local bishops 
in asuncion rene recalde president of the paraguayan lay 
movement group told the catholic radio station caritas he was 
pleased with the announcement and that the hourlong meeting would 
go on as planned tuesday night at a governmentcontrolled sports 
stadium 
marta de colman the groups press spokeswoman said 3800 
people were invited 30 percent of them from the church and the 
rest from social and political sectors among those invited were 
140 members of the government the governing colorado party and the 
armed forces with an even smaller number of invitees being from 
the political opposition ms colman said 
the stroessner government meanwhile announced that only 
statecontrolled television and radio will be allowed to cover the 
popes activities at each stop in that landlocked nation of 38 
million people church officials charged the omission of caritas in 
live papal coverage violated civil rights 
cancellation of the meeting would have marked the first time a 
government interfered with john pauls official itinerary on the 37 
overseas trips he has made since becoming pope nearly 10 years ago 
celebrating an openair mass in sticky heat at santa cruz a 
frontier boom town the pontiff delivered his strongest 
condemnation of drugs on the tour 
the drug trade has become a real trafficking in freedom since 
it leads to the most terrible form of slavery and sows your soil 
with corruption and death he told an audience the local radio 
estimated at 220000 
there is an urgent need not only to protect the youth from 
drug consumption but to combat trafficking itself which is a 
totally infamous activity 
john paul spoke at the citys secondary airport which us 
narcotics officials say is used primarily by cocaine runners 
in his sermon the pope ticked off a list of ills afflicting 
bolivia ranging from high infant mortality to unjust distribution 
of wealth and challenged the faithful to do something about them 
bolivia supplies nearly onethird of the cocaine that reaches 
users in the united states and western europe 
it is prepared in clandestine labs and shipped from hidden 
airstrips dotting the tropical lowlands of this eastern bolivian 
zone near the brazilian border 
santa cruz bolivias secondlargest city with 377000 
inhabitants is a major cocaine transit point it has luxurious 
homes villas and country clubs said to have been built with 
illicit drug money 
earlier friday the pope flew to tarija in bolivias southern 
wineproducing country to speak with children 
crowds surged against police lines to get near him 
the vatican concerned after john paul nearly was mobbed trying 
to leave a santa cruz auditorium thursday night held an emergency 
meeting with local police to discuss crowd control and logistics 
vatican security people said it was a question of keeping back 
enthusiastic bolivians not preventing an attack 
friday was the seventh anniversary of the gunshot wounding of 
the pope by turkish terrorist mehmet ali agca in st peters square 
in rome 
