the head of czechoslovakias roman 
catholic church has written an unusually tough letter to the 
communist premier saying churchstate relations are at the crisis 
point and that government policy must be changed 
in the letter dated april 23 and made available this week to 
emigres in vienna cardinal frantisek tomasek told premier lubomir 
strougal that police force used to break up a peaceful 
demonstration in bratislava in march showed a new policy of 
dialogue is needed 
it has become clear that the contacts between the state and 
the church have reached a crisis the letter said a copy was 
obtained by the associated press 
the policy towards the church to date can now only be 
continued at the price of using force the 88yearold primate 
wrote through force the crisis will not be solved but deepened 
catholics are conscious of their rights they will demand them 
and are prepared to make sacrifices the cardinal stressed 
relations between the communist authorities and the roman 
catholic church in czechoslovakia have been strained for years over 
the communists refusal to allow any bishops to be appointed in the 
last 15 years 
ten of the countrys 13 sees are vacant a situation the 
cardinal described as catastrophic and the three living 
bishops are all over 75 
last month the vatican and prague authorities reached agreement 
on appointing two auxiliary bishops for the prague archdiocese and 
one titular bishop for trnava in slovakia but these are not full 
bishops 
increasing anger among believers prompted about 500000 to sign 
