<TEXT>
colonial historians want to restore a 
fivemile stretch of road where paul revere was captured and the 
first shots of the american revolution were fired to the way it 
looked circa 1776 
but people who live along battle road dont exactly revere the 
idea of reverting the highway to a cow path you call turning a 
paved road into dirt progress asked one 
the section of route 2a that connects lexington and concord is 
just another highway to most but american history buffs consider 
it a hallowed site 
british troops clashed with the minutemen along the route on 
april 19 1775 in the first battle of the revolutionary war the 
british captured paul revere on the road as they retreated toward 
boston 
supporters of a national parks service plan to restore battle 
road include retired house speaker thomas p tip oneill and 
thomas boylston adams scion of the family that produced two us 
presidents and revolutionary firebrand samuel adams 
oneill lives on cape cod and adams lives in boston 
this is the most important road in america and deserves to be 
treated as such the 78yearold adams said in a recent 
interview likening battle roads significance to already restored 
historic sites like the battlefield at gettysburg 
but few people living and working along the road share adams 
enthusiasm arguing that they may be forced to leave land theyve 
worked for decades 
were history too says kathleen cook whose farm was first 
worked by her husbands grandfather 
i dont consider this progress and most people here agree 
with me said lou snay head chef at the willow pond kitchen in 
concord the last remaining business on battle road you call 
turning a paved road into dirt progress 
under the parks service plan to be made public may 20 traffic 
on most of battle road would be rerouted and the segment would be 
restored to its original dirt state 
trees now crowding much of the unoccupied land along the road 
would be cut to recreate the pastures of revolutionary days the 
crumbled stone walls built by the colonists would be rebuilt to 
waist height 
the parks service has overseen restoration of a dozen historic 
buildings along the roadway since 1959 after being empowered by 
congress to buy much of the property abutting the highway between 
meriams corner in concord and route 128 in lexington 
more modern stores and houses are being razed under lease terms 
that specify state ownership after 25 years or on the death of 
elderly owners 
more than 100 buildings have been torn down since the creation 
of minute man national historical park in 1959 leaving only 
several dozen homes still occupied 
mrs cook said federal officials first told us that we could 
stay in our homes as long as we wanted to and leave them to our 
families but then they decided we had to sell 
she said the family was told the land would be confiscated if 
they didnt 
i probably have seven or eight years left to stay she said 
when asked about her lease id like to stay here but i cant 
so im just taking one day at a time 
her 26yearold son peter gestured from atop his tractor at a 
justplowed field and said theyll keep this like it is but 
theyre tearing down our house because its not old enough guess 
you cant fight the government though 
parks service chief ranger fred szarka declined to discuss 
costs time schedules and other details of the proposed project 
before may 20 but suggested that an alternate roadway might result 
in others losing property 
there are people who think its a terrific idea closing the 
road to all vehicles but i think the issue would be whose 
backyard it the new road is going to go through he said 
