<DOCNO> AP880513-0129 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the internal revenue service on friday gave 
writers painters and other artists a partial exemption from a 
provision in the 1986 tax law that had severely restricted 
deduction of expenses of creating their works 
the irs said artists will be allowed to write off operating 
expenses over three years with a 50 percent deduction permitted in 
the first year and 25 percent in each of the next two the rule 
will apply the irs said only where the personal efforts of the 
individual are mainly responsible for the creation of a work of 
art 
the change will allow artists to deduct expenses even before a 
book or other artwork begins producing income it also will free 
artists from a significant amount of recordkeeping and paperwork 
it certainly alleviates the complexity concern these people 
have had tom evans a tax counsel for the treasury department 
told reporters he predicted the ruling will have little effect on 
government tax collections 
bills pending in congress would go even further than the relief 
provided by the irs they would allow artists to deduct all 
creative expenses in the year incurred 
bestselling biographer kitty kelley a leader in the fight to 
overturn the 1986 provision was less than cheered by fridays 
ruling but i guess 50 percent is better than nothing she said 
ms kelley spent four years working on a biography of frank 
sinatra and recalled that under the pre1986 law she was able to 
deduct travel copying government information and similar research 
expenses each year now i am working on a nancy reagan book and 
before todays ruling i wouldnt be able to deduct anything until 
after that book is published she said 
im fairly established but the young writers wont be able to 
stay in business long enough to get their books published she 
said i wonder whether mark twain faulkner or oneill would have 
produced what they did if they had had to operate under these 
rules 
a provision in the giant 1986 tax overhaul was designed so most 
taxpayers would be subject to a basically uniform set of 
requirements for capitalizing or writing off certain expenses 
the catchall change designed to produce about 35 billion in 
revenue over five years generally subjected artists to the same 
capitalization requirements affecting a large retailer or 
manufacturer 
the 1986 law allowed artists to deduct creative expenses only 
after the work produces income that in turn required an artist 
to forecast how much income a work of art would produce in the 
future in cases when an artist was working on two or more creative 
projects simultaneously it required that expenses be split among 
the projects 
thus a writer working simultaneously on a book and a magazine 
story for example would have to account separately for the 
expenses associated with the two projects no expenses of creating 
the works including researchrelated travel and costs of an 
assistant could be deducted until the projects earned money 
freelance writers authors photographers painters sculptors 
and other artists banded together to protest claiming the 
paperwork was an undue burden and that many would have to give up 
their careers since often many years pass before a work of art 
creates income 
the irs said the option is available for artistic expenses 
incurred in 1987 a person who already has filed a tax return using 
the tougher law may file an amended return 
the option may be used by taxpayers who incur production 
expenses associated with films recordings books photos 
paintings sculptures and other fineart products jewelry is 
specifically excluded 
eligible expenses include business travel depreciation 
equipment rental and repair labor and office overhead 
in most cases an artist whose creative output is sold in the 
same year it is produced likely would not excercise the option 
outlined friday that artist probably would continue writing off 
all expenses in the year they are incurred 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

