the general assembly urged the united 
states on friday not to close the plo observer mission which 
represents the palestinian people at the united nations 
in a 1362 vote israel and the united states were the only 
countries to oppose the resolution calling on the united states to 
allow the palestine liberation organization mission to operate 
under an international treaty 
it was the third time since march the general assembly had sent 
the united states such a message 
the united states is seeking a federal court order to close the 
plo mission the united nations considers the mission the sole 
legal representative of the palestinian people at the 159member 
world body 
the plo is invited to speak on all middle east issues but it 
cannot vote 
the resolution calls on the united states to honor the usun 
headquarters treaty of 1947 requiring it to allow all un 
missions including the plo representative to operate and 
discharge official functions 
but a us antiterrorism law passed by the congress in 1987 
requires closure of the plo mission and is in conflict with the 
treaty 
the international court of justice in the hague last month 
decreed that the united states is obligated to take the plo dispute 
to court the united states has defied the court order 
plo ambassador zehdi labib terzi told the assembly that 
international law must take precedence over domestic legislation 
can the un headquarters in the usa still be able to 
discharge its responsibilities fully and effectively if its host 
country is violating the headquarters treaty terzi asked will 
missions accredited to the un be able to function 
independently he asked 
