<TEXT>
business sales climbed 19 percent in march 
the largest advance in more than a year while the buildup of 
business inventories slowed the government reported friday 
the commerce department said total business sales rose to a 
seasonally adjusted 4795 billion in march it was the largest 
advance in 13 months and followed an equally strong 11 percent 
rise in february 
business inventories were up 03 percent to 720 billion the 
smallest rise since last august inventories had grown by 04 
percent in february and 07 percent in january 
analysts said the combination of booming sales and the slowdown 
in the growth of inventories should translate into continued 
strength in factory orders and production in the months ahead 
the 03 percent rise in inventories included a tiny 01 percent 
increase in unsold goods at the retail level a 02 percent rise at 
the manufacturing level and a 06 percent increase at the wholesale 
level 
david wyss an economist with data resources inc said the fact 
that inventories were rising at the wholesale level meant part of 
the buildup was occurring in imported goods and thus any needed 
production cutbacks in this area would not hurt domestic 
manufacturers 
michael evans head of a washington forecasting firm attributed 
the small increase in retail inventories to the success car 
manufacturers have had with their sales incentives at reducing 
backlogs of new cars 
the 19 percent rise in total sales was the largest increase 
since a 41 percent jump in february 1987 
it included a 17 percent rise in sales at the retail level 
however the government reported thursday that retail sales fell 
06 percent in april as bad weather and an early easter cut into 
demand 
sales in march at the wholesale level were up 08 percent while 
sales by manufacturers rose 26 percent 
the combination of rising sales and slower growth in inventories 
left the inventorytosales ratio at 150 in march down from 153 
in february that means that it would take 150 months to exhaust 
inventories at the march sales pace 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

