<TEXT>
two giant pandas from the peoples republic 
of china were making their way to the toledo zoo on friday amid an 
international war of words over whether the animals were being 
exploited 
toledo zoo officials called the dispute a slap in the face 
to the chinese 
in washington us district judge norma johnson refused 
thursday to grant a temporary restraining order being sought by the 
world wildlife fund and the american association of zoological 
parks and aquariums those groups sought to prevent the pandas from 
being shipped by air from shanghai 
but the judge said she would hold a hearing next week on a 
preliminary injunction that if granted could send the pandas back 
to china or restrict how the zoo can display them 
the pandas le le and nan nan were to arrive in toledo shortly 
after midnight friday and go on display by may 24 they are 
scheduled to spend at least 100 days at the zoo 
the zoo which has spent nearly 3 million preparing for their 
visit gave the chinese about 300000 in equipment and technical 
help in exchange 
in the suit the wildlife fund and the zoological association 
said exhibition of the pandas violates an international convention 
that prohibits trafficking in endangered species for commerical 
purposes 
we think the fish and wildlife service proceeded in a very 
hasty and inappropriate manner said ken cook executive director 
of the world wildlife fund 
he said the exhibition would increase the demand for such 
transactions from other zoos and hurt the effort to breed pandas 
meanwhile the blade of toledo reported friday that a 
highranking chinese wildlife official said he might never again 
allow pandas to come to the united states without a full apology 
from the us government for what he considers a breach of 
sincerity and mutual trust 
the newspaper said li gui ling secretary general of the china 
wildlife conservation association told members of the toledo zoo 
delegation traveling with the pandas that he is insulted by policy 
questions leveled at china by the fish and wildlife service the 
agency which issued permits for the visit and was named as a 
defendant in the federal court suit has questioned the way china 
uses fees it charges for panda loans 
the wildlife fund has been pressuring the wildlife service to 
stop what it calls chinas rentapanda policy until china can 
prove it is using those fees for panda conservation efforts 
at the same time edwin bergsmark president of the zoo board 
and head of the zoos panda delegation told the blade his lawyers 
had filed a countersuit against the wildlife fund in federal court 
in washington 
pandas are the national symbol of china and long have been 
regarded by the chinese as an ultimate gesture of good will trust 
and friendship 
</TEXT>
