socialist premier michel rocard said friday that 
national assembly elections must be called soon because centrist 
leaders are refusing to support his new government 
i have the feeling that we should hardly delay rocard told 
a news conference he said president francois mitterrand 
reelected sunday to a sevenyear term had not yet decided whether 
to dissolve the assembly and call early elections 
in a television interview later rocard said mitterrand would 
finish his consultations on the question saturday an 
indication that a decision could come over the weekend 
the constitution gives the president the power to dissolve the 
assembly and call new elections 
if we do not dissolve that would mean the government of the 
french republic does not have a majority rocard told antenne 2 
television 
the current 577member assembly elected for five years in march 
1986 has a centerright majority that backed the conservative 
government of jacques chirac who resigned tuesday after losing the 
presidential election to mitterrand 
before the election mitterrand had said he wanted a new 
socialistled government to try to work with the current assembly 
but rocard said he sought support from centrists in the assembly 
for his new government and received a public negative response 
the leadership of the centrist union for french democracy 
decided at a meeting this week to stay aligned with the right 
the socialists control only 211 seats so rocards government 
would be constantly in danger of falling if it lost an important 
vote 
there was increasing speculation that elections could be held in 
midjune the first possible date 
the calendar leaves barely two weeks for the decision if the 
tworound elections are to be held before the end of june 
mitterrand must dissolve the assembly before may 30 
no one seriously considers holding elections during the 
traditional vacation months of july and august when many french 
people leave home for weeks and pay little attention to the news 
the newlyappointed french cabinet dominated by senior 
socialist party leaders joined rocard for the first time at the 
presidential elysee palace on friday mitterrand appointed his 
cabinet on thursday night amid speculation that it was transitional 
and would not last 
all key posts went to wellknown socialists many of them 
members of the previous socialist government in power from 1981 to 
1986 
of the 26 full ministers 17 are socialists 
interior minister pierre joxe said mitterrand had wanted to draw 
centrists into the government but leading centrists wary of 
participating in a socialist government had declined cabinet posts 
mitterrand and rocard managed to woo over only three centrists 
two ministers and a deputy minister none with a significant 
political base of his own 
