<TEXT>
a federal jury friday began deciding 
whether carlos lehder rivas led efforts to flood the united states 
with colombian cocaine or was a simple businessman duped by 
american smugglers 
after seven months of trial the panel began deliberating 
shortly before noon on 11 charges against lehder and one against 
codefendant jack carlton reed the jury recessed five hours later 
and will return on saturday 
the jury which will be sequestered heard 22 weeks of testimony 
from 115 government witnesses and saw mountains of documents and 
carts of packaged cocaine the defense called no witnesses relying 
instead on closing arguments 
lehder reputed to be one of the leaders of colombias violent 
medellin cartel has been called the most important foreign drug 
smuggler to face trial in the united states a man who pioneered 
the idea of mass shipments of cocaine 
wrapping up his prosecution us attorney robert w merkle told 
the jury you either convict him of everything in this case of 
convict him of nothing in the case 
in his closing statement chief defense attorney edward r 
shohat argued that lehder was simply a businessman who wanted to 
develop the bahamian island of normans cay as a tourist resort but 
was victimized by a conspiring group of americans who told the jury 
a litany of lies 
shohat said that groups leader was ed ward a convicted drug 
smuggler who served served six years of a 20year sentence and is 
now in living under a new identity in the federal witness 
protection program 
he charged that ward a former jacksonville area salesman and 
insurance agent was given the break of a lifetime by agreeing 
to cooperate against lehder ward reduced a possible 215year plus 
life sentence and a 59 million fine to less than six years in 
prison shohat said 
if convicted lehder faces up to life plus 150 years in prison 
250000 in fines and forfeiture of his assets in the bahamas 
shohat also hammered away at what he said were inconsistencies 
in the testimony of other witnesses many of them smugglers who 
also got reduced sentences or immunity for their testimony 
these people planned to dump on mr lehder these people knew 
how to get an american express card to freedom he said 
lehder 38 was specifically charged with one count of 
conspiracy to import cocaine two counts of importation of cocaine 
and seven counts of possession of cocaine with intent to 
distribute upon conviction each count carries a penalty of up to 
15 years in prison and a 25000 fine 
he also was accused of engaging in a continuing criminal 
enterprise a charge that carries a sentence of 10 years to life 
reed faced only one charge of conspiracy and a maximum penalty 
of 15 years in prison and a 25000 fine 
the indictment said lehder and reed conspired to smuggle some 
33 tons of cocaine into the united states from colombia via 
normans cay from 1978 to 1980 actual testimony however alleged 
that nearly 20 tons was smuggled by lehders organization earning 
him about 20 million 
lehder the son of a german father and colombian mother grew up 
on the streets of new york he was sentenced to federal prison in 
1974 on a charge of auto theft and marijuana possession 
he was deported to colombia in 1975 
lehder was indicted in 1981 but remained at large until feb 4 
1987 when he was arrested by colombian officials at a ranch near 
medellin colombia following a brief gunfight he was immediately 
put on a plane and brought to the united states 
reed known as smilin jack was arrested two days later in 
a jungle hut on the east coast of panama 
jury selection began in october and testimony started on nov 
17 1987 six weeks later 
the indictment says lehder is one of the leaders of the medellin 
cartel which is reportedly responsible for the importation of 80 
percent of the cocaine into the united states valued at 8 billion 
a year 
