<TEXT>
a prominent scholar said friday the growth of 
the centralized national state in the 20th century threatens the 
united states with the same death suffered by ancient empires of 
the past 
robert nisbet retired humanities professor at columbia 
university and resident scholar at the american enterprise 
institute a conservative washington think tank praised villages 
families churches lodges and other forms of local communities as 
the best defense against excessive centralization of power 
it is in these intermediate groups and associations that the 
truest forms of community will be found nisbet said in a speech 
text distributed to reporters in advance they must be preserved 
strengthened honored 
nisbet a widely published historian and sociologist delivered 
the 17th annual jefferson lecture the highest honor conferred by 
the federal government for outstanding achievement in the 
humanities 
sponsored by the national endowment for the humanities an 
independent federal agency that underwrites research scholarship 
and education in the humanities the lecturer receives a stipend of 
10000 
the danger of large centralized bureaucracies is simply what 
we already see what is already obvious the suffocation or 
strangling of genuine thought of genuine leadership of genuine 
consensus nisbet said 
the lecturer saw hope in americans dislike for the massive 
circuitous mazelike federal bureaucracy and what he called a 
growing preference for localism with reliance on the family 
cities and states organized neighborhoods and volunteer 
associations 
if those true forms of community are not nourished he said 
if we continue to worship the national state and the national 
community we risk exposure to the fatal diseases of empires in 
history apoplexy at the center and anemia at the extremities 
</TEXT>
