complained about the units sexually hostile environment 
pratt held that the sec had violated the section of the civil 
rights act of 1964 that forbids sex discrimination and he scheduled 
a may 26 hearing to determine what sanctions to impose on the 
agency 
plaintiff without any doubt was forced to work in an 
environment in which the wro washington regional office managers 
by their conduct harassed her and other wro female employees by 
bestowing preferential treatment upon those who submitted to their 
sexual advances pratt said 
the record is clear that plaintiff and other women working at 
the wro found the sexual conduct and its accompanying 
manifestations which wro managers engaged in over a protracted 
period of time to be offensive pratt said 
pratt ruled that ms broderick 35 received a negative 
evaluation and was transferred to another division after 
complaining that male supervisors had sexual relationships with 
women employees this socializing included onthejob drinking and 
long lunch hours 
the judge also found that former sec commissioner john shad now 
ambassador to the netherlands and the agencys executive director 
george kundahl were aware of ms brodericks complaints in early 
1984 when she filed a memo outlining her allegations 
the agency which conducted its own internal investigation 
ruled against ms broderick in 1986 
s beville may ms brodericks attorney called the ruling an 
absolute unparalleled victory 
ms may said the ruling means that broderick who works in the 
corporation finances section will be entitled to back pay and 
promotions denied as a result of sex discrimination 
sec spokesman mary mccue said the agency did not have any 
comment on pratts ruling 
pratt found that within a week of joining the sec staff in 1979 
ms broderick spurned repeated offers of a ride home from staff 
counsel john hunter 
at a farewell party for a coworker in 1982 ms broderick was 
kissed by the regional administrator paul f leonard after he 
came up to her and untied her sweater 
the judge also accepted brodericks testimony that leonard and 
trial counsel jack kiefner made suggestive remarks about her dress 
and figure 
but it was the occurrence of numerous other incidents of which 
plaintiff early on became aware which for her created a sexually 
hostile or offensive working environment pratt ruled 
this in turn poisoned the possibility of plaintiffs having 
the proper professional respect for her superiors and without any 
question affected her motivation and her performance of her job 
responsibilities pratt ruled 
the washington regional office closed and many of the sec 
officials named in ms brodericks complaint were transferred to 
the newly created philadelphia regional office 
pratt discounted the testimony of leonard now retired and 
cliff kennedy the agencys philadelphia regional administrator and 
hunter as deserving little credence 
the judge found that the testimony of herbert f brooks jr now 
assistant regional administrator in philadelphia was in material 
respects false and incredible 
the judge ruled there is compelling evidence that brooks had a 
sexual relationship with a secretary who received two promotions 
and a 300 cash award and a perfect evaluation 
pratt also found that a woman staff attorney received several 
promotions during a time she socialized on the job with kennedy 
pratt also found that hunter had an affair with a secretary who 
received three promotions a commendation and two cash awards 
despite hunters admissions that he contributed to the 
secretarys evaluations pratt found he was never disciplined for 
this conduct but instead received 10 salary increases between 
october 1983 and january 1987 
