<TEXT>
many analysts who are bullish on the 
stockmarket outlook right now base their optimism on a common 
central theme that their peers are wrong about inflation 
fears of a resurgence of inflation have been spreading in the 
financial world since early this year when it become apparent that 
the economy was not slowing significantly in the wake of the stock 
market crash last fall 
alan greenspan chairman of the federal reserve board has 
spoken of the need to be watchful for signs of revived upward 
pressures on prices 
bond traders have registered their uneasiness by pushing the 
yield on longterm treasury bonds up from about 8 percent to 
nearly 9 percent over the past several weeks 
one of the big concerns is that economic growth may soon strain 
the capacity both of production facilities and the available supply 
of workers so that businesses costs will start to rise at an 
accelerating pace 
those worries intensified when the labor department reported 
that the unemployment rate fell to a 14year low of 54 percent in 
april 
hardly anybody is talking about a return to the doubledigit 
annual increases in the cost of living that bedeviled the economy 
in the 1970s and early 1980s 
even a moderate increase in inflation however could create big 
problems for stocks by prompting the federal reserve to tighten 
credit and interest rates to rise in the credit markets 
that in turn could pose the threat of an eventual recession 
and prompt investors to shun stocks in favor of alternatives such 
as interestbearing money market investments 
the problem with this bynowfamiliar refrain says charles 
laloggia a rochester ny investment adviser is that it is out 
of tune with other trends taking place in the financial world 
commodity prices are not rising sharply gold which laloggia 
describes as the financial market equivalent of an inflation 
weather vane has been going nowhere lately 
in addition laloggia believes tax reform will work as a 
counterinflationary force with its removal of such things as the 
incentive for consumers to spend using borrowed money 
i seriously doubt that inflation will reach levels sufficient 
to touch off a major rise in interest rates he concludes 
argues john rutledge a claremont calif economist the 
research we have done suggests that the tightcapacity argument for 
inflation is a yawner 
for example in last years labor market wages in the tight 
capacity sectors of the economy paper chemicals and steel rose 
less than average wage rates 
it seems that there is still a sizable army of workers who 
lost their jobs to restructuring over the past five years but still 
want to work at current wage rates 
if inflation is indeed sneaking up on the economy most analysts 
agree it would spell trouble for both the stock and bond markets 
there might have been times in the past observers acknowledge 
when a little bit of inflation was no problem or maybe even a 
plus for stocks 
but these days they say real interest rates in other 
words nominal interest rates as compared to the inflation rate 
remain at stubbornly high levels and the bond market is 
hypersensitive to any change in the inflation outlook 
if interest rates move up from their current levels they could 
quickly put a damper on both the stock market and the economy 
this same hypersensitivity suggests however that if inflation 
fears prove to be unfounded interest rates could fall 
substantially 
one of the surest ways to make money in the financial markets 
is to identify a consensus and to bet against it laloggia 
maintains and right now we have a beauty of a consensus which i 
believe will turn out to be incorrect 
</TEXT>
