<TEXT>
wholesale costs rose a moderate 04 percent in april while 
business sales and inventories moved in opposite directions in the 
previous month the government reported today 
the labor department said the steepest energy price gain in 15 
months pushed wholesale costs upward while food prices were 
modestly higher 
if the april increase held for 12 straight months inflation at 
the wholesale level would register an annual increase of 46 
percent more than double the 22 percent 1987 wholesale price rise 
the april increase coming after a 06 percent gain in march 
the sharpest rise in almost a year seems certain to add to 
concerns that inflation is reheating 
but the combination of booming sales and a slowdown in the 
buildup of inventories was considered good news for the economy 
pointing to expected increases in production in the months ahead 
the commerce department said business sales shot up 19 percent 
in march the biggest advance in more than a year while business 
inventories rose 03 percent the smallest gain in seven months 
separately on thursday an early easter bad weather and a 
bigger federal tax bite for some people combined to push retail 
sales down 06 percent in april but economists were unfazed by the 
decline which was the first setback in six months 
in other economic news the stock market was little changed and 
bond prices edged slightly lower amid increasing inflation worries 
the commerce department reported that consumers spent a 
seasonally adjusted 1316 billion at retail stores last month a 
drop of 815 million from the revised march figure 
sales had not fallen since a 08 percent setback last october 
but economists said they were not particularly concerned by the 
weakness especially because sales in march were revised upward to 
show an increase of 17 percent the march rise was the fastest 
sales advance since last august and almost twice the originally 
estimated 08 percent gain for the month 
retail sales are regarded as an important indicator of economic 
activity as consumer spending accounts for about twothirds of the 
gross national product 
on wall street the dow jones average of 30 industrials down 
3780 on wednesday recovered 215 points to 196800 in light 
trading 
brokers said traders continued to be concerned that persistent 
strength in the economy would lead to upward pressure on interest 
rates and inflation 
in the credit markets the price of the governments 30year 
issue fell pushing its yield to 922 percent from 920 percent 
late wednesday those yields are the highest since middecember 
separately the dollar finished slightly lower against most 
major currencies in dull domestic dealings oil prices edged 
slightly lower and soybean futures closed sharply lower after a 
fiveday rally 
